    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI1"/>, pp. 174-175, n. <citedRange>51</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.124</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>020900</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#stucchi1981a"/>, p. <citedRange>107</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>31.1576</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2000"/>, pp. <citedRange>165-166</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/>, p. <citedRange>100</citedRange> (date), pp. <citedRange>195-196</citedRange> (content) and pp. <citedRange>357-358</citedRange>, number 81 (text)</bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><rs type="office" key="eponymous priest"><w lemma="ἐπί">Ἐπ’</w></rs> <persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63853"><name nymRef="#Εὐμηλίδας">Εὐμηλίδα</name></persName>·
                    <lb n="2"/><w lemma="ὄρνις">ὀρνίχων</w>·
                    <lb n="3"/><w lemma="σκυλάκιον"><supplied reason="lost">σκ</supplied>υλακίων</w>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p> Sous <supplied reason="subaudible">la prêtrise d'</supplied>Eumélidas, avec les revenus des chiots et des oiseaux.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Being <supplied reason="subaudible">priest</supplied> Eumelidas, thanks to the revenues from puppies and birds.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Sotto <supplied reason="subaudible">il sacerdozio di</supplied> Eumelidas, grazie ai proventi dei cuccioli di cane e degli uccelli.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>فترة (الكاهن) إفميليديس ، شكر لأجل العائدات الناتجة عن بيع الجراء والطيور.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>This inscription is very similar to <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr020800</ref>, except for the lack of a preposition (for which see <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2000"/>, p. <citedRange>166</citedRange></bibl>).
                 Such a formulation mentions simply the origin of the expense made for the monument. The syntax and meaning were correctly interpreted by <bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI1"/></bibl>, who rejected 
                 the interpretation of <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr020800</ref> by its first editor, Ferri.</p>   
             <p>In the absence of any mention of a deity for whom the offering was intended, Oliverio guesssed that it was both Hekate (because of the puppies) and Demeter (because of the birds,
                 which he thought were poultry), but neither the formula nor the finding-place match this hypothesis. Later on, <bibl><ptr target="#stucchi1981a"/>, p. <citedRange>107</citedRange></bibl> 
                 supposed that birds were clues for divination, which is acceptable neither for syntax nor for meaning.</p> 
             <p>At <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/></bibl>, we were able to relate the two inscription to the new <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr125600</ref>), which has the same formula, but mentions as recipient Apollo, 
                 in whose sanctuary both afore mentioned bases were found. The dossier is now enriched by <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/></bibl>, who offers a new interpretation of 
             <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr127500</ref>. He shows that the revenues came probably from small taxes collected on occasion of sacrifices of puppies and birds to deities whose 
             cult was organised in Apollo's sanctuary and within the framework of his cash box.</p>
                <p>For a possible mention of this priest, see <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr093600</ref>. His priesthood is placed by <bibl><ptr target="#rosamilia2023"/></bibl> between ca. 370 and 335 BC.</p>
         </div></body>
    </text>
